<DOC><DOCNO> AP890309-0123 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-09-89 2129EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Refugees     03-09 0365</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Asia-Refugees,0379</SECOND><HEAD>International Conference Aims to Solve Refugee Problem</HEAD><BYLINE>By HARI S. MANIAM</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An international conference onIndochinese refugees ruled out repatriating asylum-seekers who aredeemed not to be fleeing political persecution, officials saidThursday.   Delegates from 30 nations ended their three-day meeting endorsinga draft action plan for consideration at the InternationalConference on Indochinese Refugees in Geneva in June.   Chairman Majid Mohamed told a news conference the plan would help``provide durable solutions to the Indochinese refugee problem.''   The draft plan suggests Vietnam launch a campaign stressing therisks and hardships of fleeing by boat and work to end illegaldepartures by ``boat people.'' It also calls on Vietnam to makelegal departures easier.   Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, the Philippines and othercountries in the region have agreed to provide only temporary asylumfor refugees. Western nations were urged to take in refugees left incamps in Southeast Asia.   Officials speaking on condition of anonymity said the conferencevoted not to recommend a deadline by which asylum-seekers would bescreened to decide whether they qualified for resettlement in theWest.   Officials said some Southeast Asian countries had asked theconference to recommend forcible repatriation of boat people andothers fleeing their countries for reasons other than politicalpersecution.   ``The rules are very clear ... whenever refugees are repatriated,it has to be on a voluntary basis,'' said Jean Pierre Hocke, theUnited Nations high commissioner for refugees.   The officials said the Vietnamese delegation, led by DeputyForeign Minister Vu Khoan, had agreed at the conference to take backanyone who wanted to return voluntarily.   Western delegations present said they might take in additionalrefugees, and step up financial aid to help implement the plan.   So far, 150,000 people have emigrated legally from Vietnam underthe Orderly Departure Program.   There are about 300,000 Indochinese refugees in Southeast Asia.About 1.5 million have been resettled since the outflow began 10years ago, more than 800,000 of them in the United States, officialssaid.   Majid said the plan would be sent to U.N. Secretary GeneralJavier Perez de Cuellar in New York for the Geneva conference June13-14.</TEXT></DOC>